@page "/danger"
    <BodyElement CssClass="danger" />

    <h1>The body of this page has a CSS class 'danger' applied.</h1>
    <p>
        We did it by including: <code>&lt;BodyElement CssClass="danger" /&gt;</code>
    </p>
    <p>
        Go to
        <a href="/" title="Click here to visit a page with the CSS class 'danger' on the <body> element">a page</a>
        with no CSS class!
    </p>
    <h1>Did you know...?</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>
            You can also set the <code>body</code> element's <code>lang</code> attribute by using the <code>Language</code> property
            of the <code>BodyElement</code> Blazor component. Try setting it to "en-GB" (British English) or "ES-mx" (Mexican Spanish).
        </li>
        <li>
            You can also set the <code>body</code> element's <code>dir</code> attribute by using the <code>TextDirection</code> property
            of the <code>BodyElement</code> Blazor component. Try setting it to "rtl" (right-to-left) or "ltr"
            (left-to-right, the default). This would be useful if you had to display text in a language that reads from right to
            left, like Arabic or Hebrew.
        </li>
    </ul>